<link href="adcp.css" rel="stylesheet"><entry><xh5> have a tiger by the tail • hold an eel by the tail</xh5><p> <i>have a tiger by the tail</i>—(also: catch a tiger by the tail) engage in an undertaking which may prove extremely dangerous or difficult: Everybody seems to have their own opinion on how the concert will go: they <u>have a tiger by the tail</u> and are not sure themselves how to handle the huge crowd of fun seekers. </p><p><i>hold an eel by the tail</i>—(also: catch an eel by the tail) attempt to control an elusive person or situation: He imagined I was in his power at Augsburg; he thought he had me; but he was <u>holding an eel by the tail</u>.</p><p> <div class="note">Note</div> Neither expression correlates in meaning with the phrase <b>have the world by the tail</b>—enjoy success and happiness: After all, the guy <u>had the world by the tail</u>—first class travel and first class hotels, money, glamour, beautiful women...</p> </entry>
